    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-31T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-31T02:00:00-05:00" n="534"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/13595: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-31T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >July 31, 1941—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 1—9:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1042. My 981, July 19, 7 p.m. With further reference to the conditions stipulated
                    for the surrender of the Vichy forces in French Somaliland the Legation is
                    confidentially informed that the British have specified that capitulation must
                    be direct to the Free French and that any counter-proposal in this respect will
                    be refused; that the Free French will be provided necessary supplies for the
                    relief of the population following surrender; that persons not wishing to join
                    the Free French will be repatriated but that this privilege will not be extended
                    to persons found guilty of sabotage of harbor or railway facilities which should
                    be handed ever intact. It is explained <pb facs="0603" n="591" xml:id="pg_591"/>
                    that the essential differences between the cases of Syria and French Somaliland
                    are that the latter has colonial status and that it is anticipated that
                    capitulation when effected will be without hostilities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
